{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "There is a difference between the subject of Descartes's metaphysics and the subject of Descartes's ethics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The subject of Descartes's metaphysics is a self that is substantially complete with only a capacity for pure understanding; the subject of Descartes's ethics is the living human being with the body-involving capacities of sensation, perception, imagination and voluntary motion, as well as pure understanding.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "The subject of Descartes's metaphysics has all and only those capacities required for scientia about the physical world.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "The subject of ethics has all and only those capacities required for being a self-perfecting, decisive agent with no grounds for practical regret.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Some of the capacities required for scientia about the physical world are capacities required for ethics, since the pure understanding and its methods of controlled assent are in play in both cases, but upright practical life requires further capacities besides.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "But even if there is no inconsistency in Descartes's conception of the metaphysical subject, it might be thought that Descartes betrays the much-vaunted foundational role of his metaphysics by giving any role in it to the subject of as derivative a science as ethics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "I am going to suggest that this thought, too, is mistaken.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The subject of ethics is not brought into the metaphysical writings in such a way as to compromise their foundational character.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Meditation Six is the second place where Descartes considers his own nature at length.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Since I can be clearly and distinctly conceived minus perception and imagination, they do not belong to my nature.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "For the purposes of metaphysics immateriality alone constitutes one's nature; but for the purposes of ethics one's nature is composite.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The Passions of the Soul is an ethical treatise in the sense that it specifies the nature of an unobvious sort of well-being that human beings can attain, and states schematically the means of attaining it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "There is a systematic connection between the subject presupposed by ethics and the inclusive conception of my nature found in Meditation Six.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "If my nature is the sum total of the goods of body, the goods of mind, and the goods of mind-body union, then ethics is the science of preserving or increasing all of those goods.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "The task that the metaphysics has to discharge is that of showing that human beings are not of such a nature as to be deceived about what seems most evident to them.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Metaphysics and ethics are both about self-control, and of detaching ourselves from the body.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "The metaphysical self and the ethical self are distinct but related.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "The ethical self is not simply the metaphysical self plus a body, but rather the set of capacities required for the cultivation of the whole range of goods bestowed on me by God, whereas the metaphysical self is only the set of capacities required for the pursuit of scientia in the face of the possibility that I might be able to make mistakes even about that which is most evident to me.",
      "label": "premise"
    }
  },
